wireless network w shaw s w wong n cheng x zhu k balasubramanian m maier and lg kazovsky ieee osa j of lightwave technology 2007 10 30 research projects title grow net grid reconfigurable optical and wireless network abstract to meet the demands of next generation access networks a flexible and scalable deployment will be necessary grow net plans to achieve this by providing blanketed broadband access in metropolitan areas using a hybrid optical and wireless network the capacity of optical networks and flexibility of wireless networks provide for a symbiotic relationship that allows for economic and scalable deployment title next generation optical access networks abstract this project is investigating next generation broadband access networks title gobit green office building information technology abstract this project aims to design green energy efficient information technologies for next generation office buildings title cupella abstract this project seeks to design green energy efficient access and in home networks for residential access with a particular focus on customer premises equipment where much of the energy is consumed title hyperflow abstract this project seeks to a next generation internet architecture that would gracefully integrate both current ip networks and addition higher performance flow networks optimized for large transactions this is a joint project between my group at stanford pnrl mit and utd title qpar quasi passive reconfigurable optical devices abstract this projects seeks to design novel devices for future green networks our devices don t consume any energy in the steady state and only a minimum energy during reconfiguration stay connected itunes icon google+ icon facebook icon twitter icon linkedin icon stanford university school of engineering 475 via ortega stanford california 94305 4121 650.725 1575 1997 2012 stanford university all rights reserved accreditation info terms of use copyright complaints contact us
